glove = GlobalVectors$new(
  rank = 50, # 
  # 50300
  x_max = 10, # 
  # glovehttp://nlp.stanford.edu/pubs/glove.pdf
  )

  tcm, 
  n_iter = 25, # 
  convergence_tol = 0.001,
  # n_threads = 8
  ) # **

#

word_vectors = wv_main + t(wv_context)

suppressMessages(library(data.table))

# movie_review text2vec
data("movie_review") 
setDT(movie_review) # data.table
setkey(movie_review, id) # 

# head(movie_review)

train_idx <- sample(nrow(movie_review), 0.8 * nrow(movie_review)) # 
train_set <- movie_review[train_idx] # 
test_set <- movie_review[-train_idx] # 
# print(head(train_set)) # 
it_train = itoken(
  train_set$review, # 
  preprocessor = tolower, 
  tokenizer = word_tokenizer, 
  ids = train_set$id,
  progressbar = FALSE
  )
vocab_train = create_vocabulary(it_train, ngram = c(1L, 2L))

# test_sampletrain
it_test = itoken(
  test_set$review, # 
  preprocessor = tolower, 
  tokenizer = word_tokenizer, 
  ids = test_set$id,
  progressbar = FALSE
  )

vocab_test = create_vocabulary(it_test, ngram = c(1L, 2L))

bigram_vectorizer = vocab_vectorizer(vocab_train)

Feature hashing

feature hashingDTM

If you are not familiar with feature hashing (the so-called hashing trick) I recommend you start with the Wikipedia article, then read the original paper by a Yahoo! research team. This technique is very fast because we dont have to perform a lookup over an associative array. Another benefit is that it leads to a very low memory footprint, since we can map an arbitrary number of features into much more compact space. This method was popularized by Yahoo! and is widely used in Vowpal Wabbit.

performance

h_vectorizer = hash_vectorizer(hash_size = 2 ^ 14, ngram = c(1L, 2L))

dtm_train = create_dtm(it_train, h_vectorizer)

  x = dtm_train_tfidf, #
  y = train_set$sentiment, #label 
  family = "binomial", # logit
  alpha = 1, # 1 for lasso, 0 for 
  type.measure = "auc", # 
  nfolds = NFOLDS,
  keep = TRUE, # 
  thresh = 1e-3, # 
  maxit = 1e3 # 
  )
